We were driving home after 10pm last night and there was a large rock (literally football sized) in the center lane of the freeway. It was drizzling and dark, fair amount of cars so I couldn’t swerve or change lanes. Instant flat tire 😬

We are very grateful we were able to pull over to the shoulder (thanks to all the jerks who honked at us like we were driving really slowly w our hazard lights on for fun 🙄), didn’t cause an accident, had no further damage to our car, weren’t hit while waiting in the shoulder, and that our tow truck driver was able to safely finish his very dangerous job. 

Drivers, if you don’t have AAA, I really recommend it. It’s so affordable and worth every penny in these situations. 

Got a new tire today and saw this beautiful rainbow on the way home 🌈

#amyanderson #theotheramyanderson #aaa #flattire #reels #reelsinstagram

🎂 HAPPY 18th BIRTHDAY BOB BARKER THE WONDER CHIHUAHUA! 🎂

I’m a few days late to post, but on Saturday, February 18, this tiny queen turned EIGHTEEN! We had a quiet celebration with some Ben & Jerry’s Doggie Dessert ice cream. 

Bob Barker has been with me since she was an 8 week old puppy and her personality is so special; she loves people, she’s whip smart, sassy, and determined. When she was young she was fast like a whippet and would race them at the dog park! 

Bob has helped me raise Aubrey to be a gentle animal lover and has been the straight up boss lady of every pet that has come into our home. We love her so much and every day with her is a gift.

To be clear, this post isn’t for sympathy. I keep getting asked about how hyped I am for the movie, Joy Ride, and I’ve been invited to see it many times. I’m happy any time Asian Americans are leading in entertainment but I also am conflicted about the storyline of the film. It’s difficult feeling these things side by side but it is often the reality for transnational and transracial adoptees. This ever present duality. 

This is me at the Yongsan train station in Seoul, December 2008. It’s where I was supposedly left as a newborn baby and found on the morning of Sept 3, 1972. 

During my birth search trip to Korea, I was taken to the station to see “where I was found” directly after a gut-punch of a visit to the Holt adoption offices. My guide asked me if I wanted a photo and I didn’t really know what to say. Now I’m glad I have the photo, but you can maybe tell, by the look on my face, that it was a real joy ride. 

I am 50 years old and I am still looking for my biological family. I still don’t know my birthdate. If I had a name. Where I was born. 

Adoption is trauma. 

#amyanderson #theotheramyanderson #adoption #koreanamericanadoptee #adoptionistrauma #birthsearch #adoptee #adopteevoices #joyride #holtinternational #adoptionisnotajoyride #adoptionisnotajoke

Thailand Pt. 4
Ok folks - here's the elephant content from Chiang Mai and I'd like to say something about the ethicality of the sanctuary that we visited. 

I know some people are very opposed to any kind of animal tourism, including zoos, animal encounters, etc. and I'm very careful not to patronize businesses that are unethical towards animals. 

Elephants certainly are exploited all over Thailand and all over the world in different capacities. I did a lot of research and from what I could tell, Chailai Orchid seems to be doing it right. There is no riding the elephants or them doing tricks or performing. In Thailand, elephants have been domesticated for 1000s of years and because of loss of habitat, they no longer live in the wild. They are actually given livestock status and the elephants at Chailai are tame and gentle and aren't safe in the wild. 

The mahouts were gentle and mainly used their voices to communicate with the elephants. Their website said the mahouts carry bull hooks only for extreme emergencies but we never saw a bull hook. 

The profits from Chailai go to maintaining the resort, care of the elephants, and supporting the anti-trafficking org, Daughters Rising. The local indigenous girls are at high risk for trafficking because of poverty. 

I can honestly say these elephants looked about as happy as a domesticated elephant could be and they seemed to enjoy being around the people. They were like giant dogs and they knew when there were people they were going to get attention and treats. The mama trusted people to pet and feed her baby - they were completely relaxed. 

It was an amazing experience. 

The cabin was glamping and anyone who knows me knows how much I HATE camping - so I was definitely out of my comfort zone but it was just one night and it was totally worth it. 

The food was great and the staff was very friendly and helpful. 

Also, that baby elephant was such a naughty little toddler and we loved her so much! So cute! 

🐘❤️🐘❤️🐘

Thailand Pt. 7
One of our favorite things to do when we visit a different city is to go on a food tour. It's an awesome way to experience the unique sights, sounds, smells, and tastes of a city. Often to locations we'd never visit on our own. 

In Bangkok, we took a food tour through Chinatown and tried several dishes - both Thai and local Chinese - at some amazing spots. Our tour guide, Mai, was great at leading us down hidden alleys, through massive street market crowds, and across roads of busy city traffic. We had a really nice, diverse group of people from all over the United States and Australia. 

Afterward, Mai was kind enough to negotiate a Thai price for a tuk tuk ride back to our hotel which was a wild 15 minute race through the night streets of Bangkok, tummies stuffed and heads full of memories. 

What we ate:
Kao phad Kra prow kai: stir fried chicken w basil & chili on rice
Somtam Thai: Thai papaya salad

Khanom jeeb kung: shrimp dumplings
Salapao sai moo deang: steamed bao with red pork 

Kao-kha-moo: stewed pork knuckle w rice

Pa tong ko: Chinese donut w pandan custard

Kouy teaw ped: duck noodle soup (with Leo lager!) 

Khanom buang: Thai crispy pancake

Bualoy nam khing: black sesame dumplings in ginger tea
